  "body": "View this post on the web at https://museguided.substack.com/p/the-hyperreal-self\r\n\r\n“The simulacrum is never what conceals the truth – it is the truth that conceals there is none. The simulacrum is true.” \r\n(Ecclesiastes, as cited by Baudrillard. The provocation here is that Baudrillard misattributed this to the Ecclesiastes. It was his own formulation, disguised as scripture… a fitting entrance for my essay about copies without originals.)\r\nThe sharpest critics of a system are always, eventually, swallowed by it. Baudrillard knew this. He would have had a perfect Instagram. Monochromatic. Aphoristic. Carefully absent. He would have posted exactly once a month, a blurred photograph of a desert highway, no caption, and the engagement would have been astronomical. He understood seduction too well not to weaponise it. He would have known that the most powerful simulacrum is the one that pretends it isn’t there.\r\nThe radical becomes the brand. The manifesto becomes the mood board. The commune becomes the co-working space. The revolution becomes a capsule collection. The warehouse rave becomes the wellness festival. And I, who can recite the four stages of simulation from memory, still check my phone before my feet touch the floor in the morning. Theory is one thing. The dopamine hit is another.\r\nWhat Baudrillard diagnosed in 1981, the slow murder of the real by its own copies, was, sadly, not a distant catastrophe but a neurological renovation.\r\nWe didn’t lose reality. We just became more interested in its reflection.\r\nBaudrillard’s prophecy was not that reality would disappear, it’s still here, obstinately, but that it would dissolve into a hall of mirrors so convincing we would forget which reflection began the game. In “Simulacra and Simulation”, he mapped the slow death of the real, from faithful representation to distortion, from mask to counterfeit, until finally, images became more real than life itself.\r\nWelcome to the hyperreal: Disneyland, Prada, the Coachella desert where the warehouse rave went to die and be reborn as a wellness retreat for rich nostalgia!\r\nMy best friend (who inspired me to write this essay) once described modern dance festivals as a simulacrum of the 1990s warehouse rave. He was right, and what he noticed goes deeper than aesthetics. The rave was dirty, dangerous, a feral experiment in collective dissolution. Nobody was building a personal brand. Nobody was curating their experience for later distribution. The air was a democracy of bodies, no stories, just heat and sound and the democratic sweat of strangers who would never meet again. You didn’t attend the rave. You were just briefly erased by it.\r\nThe festival is something else, sanitised transcendence, a brand partnership disguised as rebellion. You pay for the illusion of freedom, then queue for overpriced water behind someone filming a reel. The glow sticks are now biodegradable. The influencers arrive pre-bathed. The spontaneity is stage-managed by corporate sponsors who understand, with great precision, that rebellion is a lucrative demographic.\r\nBut here’s what makes this genuinely vertiginous rather than merely sad… the simulacrum doesn’t hide its falsity. It flaunts it. It sells you the idea that you know it’s fake, and that knowing makes you superior. We no longer fall for illusions; we subscribe to them knowingly, perform our irony like it’s authenticity. Postmodernism was supposed to liberate us from naïveté. Instead, it industrialised it.\r\nThe Avatar Age: Who Needs a Body When You Have a Brand?\r\nOur avatars are now our truest selves or at least the ones that receive the most applause. The body has become a data-gathering instrument for the profile: every step, heartbeat, and meal logged for conversion into content. Instagram (and not only, to be entirely honest, since I see this phenomenon more and more present on Substack Notes as well) mediates experience and it colonises it. The photograph precedes the moment. We no longer attend concerts; we document attendance. The pixel precedes the pulse.\r\nI know a woman who, before any significant trip, prepares a mental shot list. Not consciously. It happens automatically now, like breathing. She walks into a room and she’s already framing it. She sits at a café table, and her hand moves toward her phone before the coffee arrives. She doesn’t perform for anyone in particular. She performs for the archive, for the future self who will scroll back and require proof that the present was lived beautifully enough.\r\nSo, I wouldn’t say it’s vanity but something stranger. It’s pre-emptive nostalgia. We document the moment in order to feel it later, more safely, at a remove. The live version is too unruly, too threaded with boredom and discomfort. The archive is edited, lit, and approximately true.\r\nWhat’s haunting is that it works! The dopamine is real. The tiny electric jolt when someone responds to your post is a neurochemical yes, you exist. The hyperreal rewards us more reliably than reality ever did. Love doesn’t always call back. Social media does.\r\nThe avatar is more emotionally consistent than the human who made it.\r\n“When the real is no longer what it was, nostalgia assumes its full meaning.” Jean Baudrillard, “Simulacra and Simulation”\r\nThe Religion of the Real (and Why It’s a Cult)\r\nThere’s a curious paradox at play. The more our lives migrate into screens, the more we fetishise the “real”. We pay for “authentic” sourdough, “raw” retreats, “unfiltered” influencers who film themselves crying in bed in the morning, the mascara precisely smudged, the light a flattering grey. Authenticity has become the most sophisticated mask. Every “candid” shot is rehearsed. Every “messy” confession pre-approved by a brand strategist in a linen shirt.\r\nPerformance?! Yes, it’s performance aware of itself as performance, which, according to Baudrillard, is the final stage of simulation… when illusion and awareness merge into one indistinguishable substance.\r\nThe influencer crying on camera does not lie. She performs sincerity inside an economy that monetises breakdowns. The act of being real has become a market category. And the market, as always, is more than happy to supply what we demand.\r\nWe mistake rawness for truth because both hurt a little, but one sells better.\r\nThe problem isn’t that we fake it. Humans have always performed. Every love letter is a performance, every condolence, every dinner party. The problem is that we now outsource meaning to metrics. A private joy that can’t be screen-captured silently, guiltily feels insufficient. We demand receipts for intimacy. And if it can’t be posted, did it even happen?!\r\nA man once told me he couldn’t fall in love with someone who didn’t have a social media presence. He needed to know what she looked like online. As if reality were a translation, not the original text.\r\n“We see the world as being outside ourselves, although it is only a mental representation of it that we experience inside ourselves.”                                  René Magritte, on “La Condition Humaine”\r\nThe Warehouse Was Always a Temple\r\nLet’s return to the rave! I am not nostalgic, but I like to act as an archaeologist.\r\nTo sweat, strobe, and bass in a dilapidated space where legality hung by a thread and nobody had a brand deal with anyone. Those nights were feral. There was something genuinely sacred about them, not in spite of the chaos, but because of it! The dissolution of the self in collective noise is an ancient ritual. The warehouse just had a better sound system than the oracle at Delphi.\r\nFast forward, the modern festival replicates the aesthetics but not the ethics. You buy transcendence in pre-measured doses, timed to the setlist. The experience is optimised for its own representation. You don’t dance to forget the world; you dance to belong to it, to produce content that proves you were there, that you felt things, that you are the kind of person who attends events like this.\r\nThe new version is not false, it’s just that it no longer needs to be real. The simulation has replaced the source. You don’t miss the warehouse because you never knew it; you miss what the simulation implies was once possible. Nostalgia for a freedom you never had… and that’s the genius of the hyperreal.\r\nThere’s something really heartbreaking about that. The rave once promised escape from the self. The festival promises a better, more photogenic version of it. Not transcendence. Curation through motion. The ecstasy is real. The context is managed.\r\nThe Digital Mirror and Its Moral Fog\r\nBaudrillard warned that when the real and the copy collapse into one another, moral judgement loses its footing. How do you critique a performance that knows it’s a performance? How do you resist a system that anticipates your rebellion and merchandises it before you act?\r\nThe algorithm gives you the illusion of power: control your narrative, craft your story, live your truth! The irony is that truth, in that sentence, functions grammatically as a product… possessible, editable, brandable. The algorithm feeds you a mirror, and the mirror feeds you back your own desires, slightly filtered for marketability. This is the curation so perfect you forget you’re being curated.\r\nSometimes I try to trick it. I click on unlikely things: a fishing village in the Faroe Islands, a grandmother demonstrating a recipe in a language I don’t speak, an obscure documentary about agricultural machinery from 1974. For a while, the feed becomes strange again. Then the algorithm recalibrates, discreetly, without drama, and steers me back toward profitable longing.\r\nReality is stubborn. Simulation is adaptive.\r\nThe Erotic Logic of Simulation\r\nThere’s something genuinely erotic about all this, the way the phone hums when someone responds, the way the avatar becomes an object of desire, the way the screen offers proximity without exposure. Desire thrives on distance, and the hyperreal perfects distance while pretending to abolish it. It’s the pornography of intimacy, the fantasy of closeness without the risk of contact.\r\nBaudrillard argued that the real is disappearing because of seduction, not oppression. The image seduces more effectively than life ever could. The ancient art of seduction, once a dance of mystery, accumulation, misreading, risk, is now predictive analytics. The algorithm already knows your type before you do. It knows which sentence will make you slow your scroll, which eyes will make you stop entirely.\r\nRomance has been replaced by targeting.\r\nAnd yet! Despite all this, one can fall in love with someone’s writing on a screen. Not their photo, not their curated smile, but the rhythm of their thought, the specific pressure they apply to a sentence. Something genuinely undetermined passes through the glass.\r\nMaybe the simulacrum doesn’t always kill the real. Sometimes it smuggles it back in under disguise….\r\nInfluencers, Saints, and the New Iconography\r\nMedieval cathedrals were built to awe peasants into faith. Social media performs the same function, only the doctrine is aspirational rather than theological. Influencers are our saints, their lives curated to inspire both envy and devotion. Their miracles are engagement rates. Pilgrimage has become pilgrimage-lite: fly somewhere scenic, find yourself, post evidence.\r\nBaudrillard wrote that the icon once represented God, then replaced Him. Our icons now represent nothing but themselves, yet wield divine influence. They don’t sell products but aspirational ontology, a way of being so smooth it dissolves the friction that is the hallmark of the real.\r\nThe algorithm replaced the priest. Confession moved to captions. The penance is engagement.\r\nAnd somewhere in the comment section, beneath the affirmations and the thin-lipped emojis, an absolutely genuine human ache for transcendence persists. That ache is not fake. It’s just misdirected, which might be the oldest story there is.\r\nThe Politics of Pretend\r\nThe hyperreal doesn’t stop at lifestyle; it long ago colonised politics. We don’t elect leaders anymore; we elect symbols of conviction. The image of authenticity outweighs its substance. Baudrillard’s essay on the Gulf War was not a denial of bombs but a diagnosis of perception, what mattered wasn’t what happened but how it was shown, and who controlled the showing.\r\nNow, even dissent has been aestheticised. The solidarity post, the protest selfie… it’s not that they are meaningless, but that meaning itself has been flattened into gesture. You can oppose the system while unknowingly reproducing its logic. The hyperreal thrives on opposition; it absorbs outrage as efficiently as it consumes attention.\r\nWe have confused moral participation with visible participation. The revolution will be livestreamed, sponsored, and algorithmically curated for peak engagement hours.\r\nThe Psychology of Never Enough\r\nThe hyperreal is addictive because it offers what reality can’t: infinite feedback. Real life runs on delay, years between effort and reward, silence between gestures. Online, gratification is instantaneous. You become your own god, capable of summoning validation on demand. But it’s a fragile divinity; one algorithmic tweak, and the worshipers vanish.\r\nThe warehouse rave had one rule: lose yourself. The digital festival has one commandment: optimise yourself. The first dissolves the ego. The second immortalises it. No narcissism involved, only institutionalised self-preservation, the logical endpoint of a culture that has decided the individual is a brand and the brand must survive.\r\nLate at night, scrolling through photographs of yourself smiling in places you barely remember, you realise the hyperreal isn’t a dystopia imposed on us from outside but a coping mechanism we built ourselves, with extraordinary care because reality became too slow, too quiet, too indifferent to our need for witness. So, we constructed a parallel version – faster, louder, more flattering. We called it “connection”.\r\nThe Collapse of Context\r\nOne of Baudrillard’s most terrifying insights: meaning depends on absence. When everything is visible, nothing has weight. The hyperreal is total exposure. It abolishes mystery and, with it, depth. We no longer interpret, we scroll. Interpretation requires silence, distance, doubt… qualities the algorithm reads as inefficiency.\r\nI regularly attend vernissages where people spend more time photographing the paintings than looking at them. The museum had become a backdrop for digital identity. The art is no longer the object; it is the proof of attendance.\r\nDuring one of these vernissages, amid the clicking shutters, one painting stopped me cold: Caravaggio’s Incredulity of Saint Thomas. Thomas’s finger entering the wound, touching, testing, refusing to accept the copy without verification. That gesture felt almost unbearably contemporary. The original sceptic. The man who needed to feel it to believe it.\r\nMaybe the only way to resist the hyperreal is to remember that touching is different from photographing. That the wound must be contacted, not captured.\r\n“It is dangerous to unmask images, since they dissimulate the fact that there is nothing behind them.”                                                                                              Jean Baudrillard, “Simulacra and Simulation”\r\nWhere Baudrillard Was Wrong Or Not Wrong Enough\r\nHere is where I want to introduce a fracture, because Baudrillard, for all his brilliance, was also performing. The cool intellectual who has seen through everything is itself a persona. Seductive, total, and not entirely honest.\r\nHis diagnosis was correct. His prognosis was too fatalistic, and fatalism, in a philosopher, is not neutral. It is its own form of aesthetics. To say the real is gone, the simulation is total, résistance is already absorbed is to make a choice. It forecloses what it claims merely to observe. It’s a counsel of elegant despair dressed as theory.\r\nBut the theory misses the fact that the simulation is also a survival technology.\r\nConsider who uses it. The teenager in a provincial town who finds, through a screen, that people like them exist, that their particular strangeness is not a defect but a dialect with speakers elsewhere. The immigrant who maintains intimacy across ten time zones through nothing more than voice messages and photographs. The person in the grip of illness who is able, through the avatar, to continue to be someone when the body has temporarily stopped cooperating. For these people, the hyperreal is not a substitute for the real. It is the frame that holds the real up while repairs are made.\r\nBaudrillard wrote from a position of such drastic detachment that he could afford to declare the real lost. Most people cannot afford that conclusion. They need the copy to survive long enough to find their way back to the original.\r\nThis doesn’t make the simulation innocent. It makes it ambivalent, which is far more interesting, and far more honest, than either celebration or condemnation.\r\nThe copy as lifeboat. The avatar as placeholder self. The hyperreal not as the death of the real, but as its emergency accommodation… temporary, imperfect, and sometimes all there is.\r\nLiving Among Echoes\r\nI sometimes wonder what Baudrillard would say if he saw us now. Probably nothing. He’d light a cigarette, look at his phone – yes, he would have a phone – and say: I told you! He might even post it.\r\nBut I suspect he couldn’t have predicted the emotional precision of our self-simulation. The post about burnout that goes viral not because it’s false but because it isn’t… quite. The tears edited to music that nonetheless contain real salt. The sincerity so rehearsed it passes as art and occasionally is.\r\nAnd here is the paradox I can’t escape… if everything is simulated, then so is our longing for the real. And yet that longing hurts. Pain, by definition, can’t be faked without becoming something else entirely. Maybe that’s our last remaining thread, not to the real, exactly, but to the fact of our own interiority.\r\nThe simulacrum may counterfeit joy competently. It cannot counterfeit grief without producing something grotesque. That’s where we still bleed something undoctored.\r\nI once didn’t use my accounts for a month. I wanted to feel “real life” again. Instead, I felt phantom pain, the way amputees describe sensation in absent limbs. I realised the hyperreal wasn’t external, it had rewired my perception. Even walking through Paris felt like scrolling; every corner looked like content I was failing to capture. The map had replaced the territory so completely that I had to relearn how to read the land.\r\nIt took weeks. But eventually, slowly, badly, I remembered how to look at something without immediately converting it into evidence that I had been there.\r\n“Perhaps all the dragons in our lives are princess who are only waiting to see us act, just once, with beauty and courage.”                                                           Rainer Maria Rilke, “Letters to a Young Poet”\r\nWhat Remains\r\nWe cannot return to the warehouse. And perhaps we shouldn’t, that past is idealised too, by the same mechanism that makes every origin mythic. We are here, in the hyperreal, and the question is not how to escape it but how to move inside it without being entirely consumed.\r\nTo notice when the photograph is about to replace the moment. To resist, occasionally and imperfectly, the conversion of presence into archive. To remember that touching a hand is not the same as sending a hand emoji, yes, one is real and one is fake, but they work on different registers of the nervous system, and both registers matter.\r\nThe copy, Baudrillard insisted, has destroyed the original. But in my experience, and I’m choosing the word deliberately, against all theoretical hygiene, occasionally, unexpectedly, the copy mourns the original. It gestures toward what it knows it is not. And in that gesture, something passes through.\r\nI still look at my phone in the morning. I still frame things mentally before I touch them. But sometime, rarely, not as a discipline but as an accident, I look at something without reaching for it. A light across water. A face in concentration. The specific quality of a Thursday afternoon.\r\nThese moments do not last. They are not meant to. They do not require documentation. That is what makes them the realest things I know.\r\nNot the absence of the simulation. Just the memory, brief and unarchived, that something existed before it was reflected.\r\nThat’s enough! That has to be enough! And some days, strangely, it is!\r\nStill learning to look without framing, still failing, still here, unarchived, unfiltered, and therefore perhaps the truest, yours, in the unrecorded,\r\nTamara\r\nNot a tip jar. A ledger for what you underlined in your mind. [ https://substack.com/redirect/a88ab3e5-00aa-41b5-afef-7ef90581fc98?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]\r\nMuseguided exists because of its readers. If you want to be part of it, as a free or paid subscriber, I would be glad and grateful to have you.\r\n\r\nUnsubscribe https://substack..gV40rRMMuCKe1LV0NiJnT8Ejr2tH3yawSUvzqFe-1IY?",
